arks of southeast Missouri. A particularly large discrepancy is in the Edwards Plateau of central Texas where MEGAN v2.1 is too high by a factor of 3, possibly reflecting errors in land cover. The lower isoprene emissions inferred from our inversion, when implemented into GEOS-Chem, decrease surface ozone over the southeast US by 1-3ppb and decrease the isoprene contribution to organic aerosol from 40 to 20%.},
author = {Kaiser, Jennifer and Fried, Alan and {St. Clair}, Jason M. and Zhang, Lin and {Gonz{\'{a}}lez Abad}, Gonzalo and Travis, Katherine R. and Jacob, Daniel J. and Wisthaler, Armin and Crounse, John D. and Fisher, Jenny A. and Zhang, Xuesong and Zhu, Lei},
doi = {10.5194/acp-18-5483-2018},
file = {:home/jesse/Dropbox/PHD/References/Kaiser2018_IsopreneInversion.pdf:pdf},
isbn = {1854832018},
journal = {Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics},
number = {8},
pages = {5483--5497},
title = {{High-resolution inversion of OMI formaldehyde columns to quantify isoprene emission on ecosystem-relevant scales: application to the southeast US}},
